	<ul class="children">

	<li class="comment odd alt depth-3" id="comment-6784">
	<article >

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/c7937f5f8b656d054710b0660f2df247?s=48&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/c7937f5f8b656d054710b0660f2df247?s=96&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' loading='lazy'/><span itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.mensmaximus.de/" class="comment-author-link" rel="external nofollow" itemprop="url">Michael Weichselgartner</a></span> 			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2015-10-08T20:02:00-07:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/2015/10/brute-force-amplification-attacks-against-wordpress-xmlrpc.html#comment-6784">October 8, 2015</a></time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>To disable the xmlrpc interface paste the following code into the functions.php file of your child theme:<br />
add_filter(&#8216;xmlrpc_enabled&#8217;,&#8217;__return_false&#8217;);</p>
<p>To disable only some methods e.g. the system methods paste the following code into the functions.php file of child theme:</p>
<p>add_filter( &#8216;xmlrpc_methods&#8217;, &#8216;mmx_remove_xmlrpc_methods&#8217;);<br />
function mmx_remove_xmlrpc_methods( $methods ) {<br />
 unset( $methods[&#8216;system.multicall&#8217;] );<br />
 unset( $methods[&#8216;system.listMethods&#8217;] );<br />
 unset( $methods[&#8216;system.getCapabilities&#8217;] );<br />
 return $methods;<br />
}</p>
		</div>

		
		
	</article>
	<ul class="children">

	<li class="comment even depth-4" id="comment-6790">
	<article >

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/f049fe6727867307ba8f993721b21021?s=48&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/f049fe6727867307ba8f993721b21021?s=96&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' loading='lazy'/><span itemprop="name">Jan R</span> 			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2015-10-09T07:13:00-07:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/2015/10/brute-force-amplification-attacks-against-wordpress-xmlrpc.html#comment-6790">October 9, 2015</a></time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Disabling XMLRPC methods is a good thing, but what it doesn&#8217;t do is stopping the POST-requests from coming in. I haven&#8217;t looked at the byte-size of the POST-requests in question, but hosting multiple WordPress sites on one (shared) web server might severely degrade performance.</p>
		</div>

		
		
	</article>
